{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Quadratic Wall"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Full self-attention computes a score between every pair of positions, producing an T×T matrix. Memory scales as O(T²): at T=4096 with 32 heads and float16, the attention matrices alone occupy ~8 GB per layer. For long-document tasks (legal, scientific, code), T easily reaches 32k–128k — at which point O(T²) memory becomes infeasible on any current hardware without approximation."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sliding-window attention (SWA) reduces this to O(T·w) by restricting each token to attend only to the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "w"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " nearest past tokens, where w is the window size. For T=32k and w=4096, SWA uses 8× less attention memory than full attention."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Full causal attention grid versus sliding-window attention with window w=3, showing active cells highlighted in each approach"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Local Attention and the Receptive Field"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "With a window of size w, token t sees directly only tokens "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "[t−w+1, …, t]"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". But across L transformer layers, information can propagate further: after k layers, a token's effective receptive field spans "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "k·w"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " positions. This is analogous to how a deep CNN with small convolutions still has a wide effective receptive field."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{receptive field after } L \\text{ layers} = L \\times w"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For Mistral 7B (L=32, w=4096), the top-layer receptive field is 32×4096 = 131,072 tokens — sufficient to cover the entire context window of 32k. Long-range dependencies are bridged by propagating information layer-by-layer through overlapping windows."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\nimport math\n\ndef sliding_window_attention(q, k, v, window: int):\n    \"\"\"\n    Causal sliding-window attention.\n    q, k, v: (B, T, d_k)\n    Attends to at most `window` past tokens (including self).\n    \"\"\"\n    B, T, d_k = q.shape\n    # Build the full T×T score matrix, then mask everything outside the window\n    scores = torch.bmm(q, k.transpose(1, 2)) / math.sqrt(d_k)  # (B, T, T)\n\n    # Causal mask: upper triangle blocked\n    causal = torch.tril(torch.ones(T, T, device=q.device, dtype=torch.bool))\n    # Window mask: positions more than `window` steps back are also blocked\n    window_mask = torch.ones(T, T, device=q.device, dtype=torch.bool)\n    for i in range(T):\n        window_mask[i, :max(0, i - window + 1)] = False\n\n    mask = causal & window_mask\n    scores = scores.masked_fill(~mask, float('-inf'))\n    attn = F.softmax(scores, dim=-1)\n    attn = torch.nan_to_num(attn)   # softmax(-inf, …, -inf) → nan; replace with 0\n    return torch.bmm(attn, v)\n\n# Quick test\nB, T, d_k, w = 2, 16, 32, 4\nq = torch.randn(B, T, d_k)\nout = sliding_window_attention(q, q, q, window=w)\nprint(out.shape)   # (2, 16, 32)\n\n# Receptive field grows linearly with depth\nfor n_layers in [1, 4, 8, 16, 32]:\n    field = n_layers * w\n    print(f'{n_layers:2d} layers × w={w}: field={field} tokens')\n# 1 layers: field=4\n# 32 layers: field=128  (covers full 128-token context)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Efficient Implementation: Block-Sparse CUDA Kernels"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The naive approach above still materialises the full T×T score matrix and masks most of it — memory is not actually saved. Efficient SWA requires a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "block-sparse or chunked kernel"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " that only computes the diagonal band. FlashAttention-2 and its extensions support this: the attention matrix is processed in tiles, and tiles outside the window band are skipped entirely."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mistral 7B uses SWA with w=4096 implemented via a rolling buffer KV cache at inference: older keys and values are evicted once they fall outside the window, keeping the cache size constant at w positions regardless of generation length."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForCausalLM\nimport torch\n\n# Mistral 7B uses sliding-window attention with w=4096\n# The model handles this transparently — no special API needed\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained('mistralai/Mistral-7B-v0.1')\nmodel = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(\n    'mistralai/Mistral-7B-v0.1',\n    torch_dtype=torch.bfloat16,\n    device_map='auto',\n)\n# Check the configured window size\nprint(model.config.sliding_window)          # 4096\nprint(model.config.max_position_embeddings) # 32768\n\n# At inference: the rolling KV cache stays fixed at w=4096 entries\n# regardless of how many tokens have been generated.\n# This means constant memory even for very long generations.\n\n# For a doc that exceeds the window, content from 4096+ tokens ago\n# is no longer directly accessible — but through layer stacking,\n# information still propagates if the model learned to do so."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Global Tokens and Hybrid Attention"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pure SWA cannot directly connect tokens more than w positions apart in a single layer. A common fix is to designate a few "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "global tokens"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (such as [CLS] or a task prompt prefix) that attend to — and are attended by — every other token regardless of distance. Global tokens act as a communication bus, allowing any local token to influence any other token in two hops: local → global → target."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mistral uses an alternating pattern: even layers use full attention, odd layers use SWA. This preserves global context in half the layers while saving memory overall. Gemma 2 adopts the same alternating scheme."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\nimport math\n\ndef hybrid_attention(q, k, v, window: int, global_indices: list):\n    \"\"\"\n    Sliding-window attention + global tokens.\n    global_indices: positions that attend/are attended by all tokens.\n    \"\"\"\n    B, T, d_k = q.shape\n    scores = torch.bmm(q, k.transpose(1, 2)) / math.sqrt(d_k)  # (B, T, T)\n\n    # Start with all positions masked\n    mask = torch.zeros(T, T, dtype=torch.bool, device=q.device)\n\n    # Allow causal local window for everyone\n    for i in range(T):\n        lo = max(0, i - window + 1)\n        mask[i, lo:i+1] = True\n\n    # Global tokens: bidirectional full attention\n    for g in global_indices:\n        mask[g, :g+1] = True   # global token attends all past\n        mask[:, g]    = True   # all tokens can attend the global token\n\n    scores = scores.masked_fill(~mask.unsqueeze(0), float('-inf'))\n    attn = F.softmax(scores, dim=-1).nan_to_num()\n    return torch.bmm(attn, v)\n\nB, T, d_k, w = 1, 12, 16, 3\nq = k = v = torch.randn(B, T, d_k)\n# Position 0 is a [CLS]-style global token\nout = hybrid_attention(q, k, v, window=w, global_indices=[0])\nprint(out.shape)  # (1, 12, 16)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "When to use SWA: "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "If your task is primarily local (language modelling, code completion, chunked document summarisation), SWA with w around 2k–8k works well and enables much longer context within a fixed memory budget. If your task requires arbitrary cross-document references or global token comparisons, full attention or a hybrid with global tokens is safer. The window size is a hyperparameter: too small and long-range information is lost; too large and the O(T·w) savings evaporate."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
